ELS, where the NUV-band and F160W trace the profile of\n(unobscured) massive stars and the stellar continuum, respectively. The\n$R_{\\rm{eff}}$ of galaxies in the PAH-band are slightly smaller ($\\sim$10\\%)\nthan those in F160W for galaxies with $\\rm{M_*\\gtrsim10^{9.5}~M_\\odot}$ at\n$z\\leq1.2$, but the PAH-band and F160W have a similar fractions of light within\n1 kpc. In contrast, the $R_{\\rm{eff}}$ of galaxies in the NUV-band are larger,\nwith lower fractions of light within 1 kpc compared to F160W for galaxies at\n$z\\leq1.2$. Using the MIRI data to estimate the $\\rm{SFR_{\\rm{IR}}}$ surface\ndensity, we find the correlation between the $\\rm{SFR_{\\rm{IR}}}$ surface\ndensity and stellar mass has a steeper slope than that of the\n$\\rm{SFR_{\\rm{UV}}}$ surface density and stellar mass, suggesting more massive\ngalaxies having increasing amounts of obscured fraction of star formation in\ntheir inner regions. This paper demonstrates how the high-angular resolution\ndata from JWST/MIRI can reveal new information about the morphology of\nobscured-star formation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 13 Jan 2023 19:03:30 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 2 Apr 2023 21:30:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-04"}
